            <header>
              <h2 class="h1">Thermoregulation of King Penguins: A Background</h2>
            </header>
            <p>King penguins (Aptenodytes patagonicus) live in extreme environments. However, they are able to maintain surprisingly high core temperatures on dry land (~37 degrees Celcius), especially compared to at sea. This is because air has a lower thermal condictivity than water, meaning that you cool down or warm up quicker in water than in the air. As well, air temperatures are often higher than water temperatures in the penguin's environment.</p>
            <p>From these insights, we know king penguins are most thermally stressed (cold) when in the water on their foraging excursions. How can they survive these harsh temperatures? Many sea mammals stay warm with thick fur (pelage) or fat on their main body. However, their appendages are more exposed: their feet are naked and their flippers have little fat and only short feathers. King penguins are adapted to let their appendages (fins and feet) remain colder than their main body. King penguins undergo a process called <i>vasoconstriction</i>, in which they massively reduce the amount of blood flowing through their appendages, reducing heat exchange between their appendages and main body. This way, a penguin's cold feet and flippers don't send much cold blood back to their trunk, which would cool down their core temperature. King penguin veins are also structured so the warm blood from their heart passes by the cold blood from their appendages to warm it up, reducing even further the cold blood coming into their main body and cooling their core temperature. Both of these adaptations may reduce heat loss to 2-6% of total heat loss compared to 19-48%.</p>
            <br>
            <p>Q1: What is more important: appendage temperature or core body temperature? Why?</p>
            <p>Q2: Reflect on why these adaptations are important for king penguins in their habitat.</p>
            <br>
            <p><img src="/images/king-penguins-hypothermic.jpg" style="width:50%; margin-top:75px"></p>
            <p>King penguins, depending on how long they stay in cold waters, can become partially or fully hypothermic. A penguin is only partially hypothermic if only it's appendages are at a low temperature, but it keep a normal core temperature. A penguin is fully hypothermic if it's core temperature is also reduced.</p>
            <br>
            <p>Q3: Why are penguin feet and flippers not more insulated to keep them warmer?</p>
            <br>
            <p>This question brings one main reason why appendages are not better insulated. When king penguins are on land for a long time, there is a possibility of overheating. This concern is mitigated by penguin flippers acting as "thermal windows." Thermal windows allow greater heat exchange with the environment than other body structures. Little heat escapes from a penguin's trunk, but they are able to cool down using their flippers and feet. By exposing greater parts of their flippers, king penguins are able to finely control their core body temperature.</p>
            <br>
            <p>Q4: Think about and explain how king penguins are also able to control their core body temperature using their feet.</p>

            <p><img src="/images/king-penguins-thermoregulation.jpg" style="width:50%; margin-top:75px"></p>
            <p>Q5: Noting the differences in position between the thermal windows (flippers and feet) of these two penguins, which penguin is warming up and which penguin is cooling down? What informs your decision?</p>
