            </header>
            <p>Researchers wanted to study how penguins warmed back up after long foraging trips. They decided to use FLIR thermal imaging cameras to study these processes. Due to a penguin's thick coat, the thermal camera cannot identify a penguins core temperture, only it's surface temperature. However, researchers could study  how penguins thermoregulate using their flippers as thermal windows.</p>
            <p>Researchers were particularly interested in this question: Do penguins which are partially hypothermic warm up differently than penguins that are fully hypothermic? Do partially and fully hypothermic penguins stop vasoconstriction at different times when warming up?</p>
