            <p>Q9: What differences do you notice between the fully and partially hypothermic populations? (Note: Look at when the temperature of the flippers begin to increase)</p>
            <br>
            <p>The researchers noted that there is a 5-minute delay to flipper warming in fully hypothermic penguins; there is no delay to flipper warming in partially hypothermic penguins. Why might that be? One possibility is that core temperature warming took precedence over appendage warming. Researchers posit that the hypothermic penguins continued to vasoconstrict their appendages to focus on raising their core temperature (during the first 5 minutes represented in the graph), then, once their internal core temperature was back to normal, they ended vasoconstriction to allow their appendages to begin warming.</p>
